AWK - It scans each line of input, tests it against patterns, and executes actions on matches. 
Think of it as a programmable grep + cut + sort with arithmetic and variables built in.
SYNTAX: awk [flags] 'pattern { action }' [file...]
NOTABLE USE CASES
- The !seen[$0]++ — it removes duplicate lines while preserving original order, something sort | uniq can't do.
  awk '!seen[$0]++' yo.txt # print unique entries in yo.txt, even  awk '!seen[$0]++' yo.txt > ymca.txt
- OTHER EXAMPLE: 
   count[...]++ #for counting.
   seen[...]++ #for remembering what has appeared.
   ++seen[...] == 2 #for finding the second copy.

-  The NR==FNR join pattern in the pipelines tab is one of the most practical things to memorise —
 it is used to join or compare two separate files based on a matching key.
 Think of it as a command-line version of an SQL INNER JOIN, a VLOOKUP in Excel, 
 or merging two dataframes in Python.
  - awk uses two built-in counters when processing files.:
   *NR (Number of Records): This is a global row counter. It starts at 1 on the first line of the first file,
   and keeps counting up continuously, across every file you pass into the command.
   *FNR (File Number of Records): This is a local row counter. It resets back to 1 every time awk opens a
   new file.
   SYNTAX - FIRST PART
   NR==FNR { array[$1]=$2; next }
    -Because NR==FNR is true, this entire block executes for every line of first file.
    -array[$1]=$2: It creates an associative array (like a dictionary or map). It uses the data in column 1 ($1)
     as a lookup key, and maps it to the value in column 2 ($2).
    -next: This is a crucial keyword. It tells awk to stop processing the current line immediately,
    skip any code that follows, and grab the next line. This ensures the second part of our script
    doesn't run while we are still inside the first file.
   --Example:
    awk 'NR==FNR { name[$1]=$2; next } $1 in name { print $0, name[$1] }' users.txt logins.txt
    #this looks up inputs from users in login and merges them, it can also be parsed into a new file with >

    awk 'NR==FNR { IPs[$1]; next } $3 in IPs' blacklist.txt access.log
    #Read a list of blacklisted IP addresses from blacklist.txt, then print only the log entries whose 
    IP address appears in that blacklist.
    #IPs in access.log is on the 3rd column

    awk 'NR==FNR { keys[$1]; next } !($1 in keys)' client.conf template.conf
    #Finding Missing Configurations (Diffing Data) show configuration keys are present in your default 
    reference template (template.conf), but are missing from a specific client machine's file (client.conf).

BUILT-IN AWK VARIABLES
The Line and Field Selectors ($0, $1, $2...) 
# $0: Represents the whole line exactly as it was read. printS the complete, unaltered raw data.
# $1, $2...$N: References specific columns. By default, awk splits these columns anywhere it sees spaces or tabs.
  e.g. awk '{print $1, $4}' tok.txt #prints first and fourth values of tok.txt

The Dynamic Tail Targets (NF, $NF, $(NF-1))
The NF variable tracks the Number of Fields (columns) on the current line. Crucially, putting
 a dollar sign in front of it—$NF—tells awk to print the value of the column numbered NF.
Why it's vital: In log files, lines often have different lengths. If line A has 4 words and line B has 7 words, 
 you can't rely on $4 to grab the final word. $NF always hits the end of the line, regardless of how messy or variable the line length is.
.e.g. awk '{print $NF}' /var/log/auth.log  # Safely prints the absolute last column of every log entry
   awk '{print $(NF-1)}' /var/log/auth.log # Safely prints the second-to-last column
NR (Number of Records): A global row counter that tracks how many total lines awk has processed since the command started.
 awk '{print NR, $0}' server.log #cats the file and each line is numbered

The Column Pair: FS and OFS
FS (Input Field Separator)
By default, awk looks at a line of text and slices it into columns wherever it sees whitespace (spaces or tabs).
FS lets you change that divider character.
Context: If you are reading a CSV file or /etc/passwd, columns aren't separated by 
spaces—they are separated by commas or colons.
How to set it: You can use the -F flag on the command line, or define it inside a BEGIN block (code that runs before awk opens the file).
awk -F ':' '{print $1}' /etc/passwd # Slicing a colon-separated file using the command-line flag
awk 'BEGIN {FS=":"} {print $1}' /etc/passwd # Doing the exact same thing inside a BEGIN block

OFS (Output Field Separator)
When you ask awk to print multiple columns separated by a comma (like print $1, $2), the comma is a placeholder. 
awk replaces that comma with whatever character is stored in OFS. By default, OFS is a single space.
*Used to convert a colon-separated file into a clean, comma-separated CSV file. 
You tell awk to read with a colon (FS) and write with a comma (OFS):
e.g awk 'BEGIN {FS=":"; OFS=","} {print $1, $3, $4}' /etc/passwd

The Row Pair: RS and ORS
RS (Input Record Separator)
By default, awk thinks "one line of text = one record." It uses the standard newline character (\n) to know when a row ends.
RS lets you change this definition entirely.
EXAMPLE: eg.log : 
User: fawaz
IP: 127.0.0.1
***
User: alex
IP: 192.168.1.1
awk 'BEGIN {RS="***\n"} {print $2, $4}' eg.log #removes the seperator *** and merges fawaz and alex

ORS (Output Record Separator)
Whenever you call the print command, awk automatically slaps ORS onto the very end of your output. 
By default, ORS is a newline character (\n), which is why every single print command starts a fresh new line on your screen
EXAMPLE: Ip.log
10.0.0.1
10.0.0.2
10.0.0.3
awk 'BEGIN {ORS=" "} {print $0}' ip_list.txt #Output: 10.0.0.1 10.0.0.2 10.0.0.3

